<subSubSection lastPageId="38" lastPageNumber="339" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,1183,2037]" lastBlockId="38.[151,1436,151,213]" lastPageId="38" lastPageNumber="339" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1831,1856]" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Needham &amp; Murphy ." authorityYear="1924" box="[332,540,1832,1856]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="segnis">
<emphasis box="[332,540,1832,1856]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Campsurus segnis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from adults of both sexes, and it can be distinguished from other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eaton" authorityYear="1868" box="[271,399,1869,1892]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[271,399,1869,1892]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Campsurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by: 1) male sternum IX with straight to broadly convex hind margin (
<figureCitation box="[1192,1291,1868,1893]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Fig. 138</figureCitation>
); 2) pedestal bases distinctly separated in the middle (
<figureCitation box="[616,715,1903,1928]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Fig. 138</figureCitation>
), parastylus very long and slender (p in 
<figureCitation box="[1178,1276,1903,1928]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Fig. 138</figureCitation>
), inner corner also projected but slightly (ic in 
<figureCitation box="[519,617,1940,1965]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Fig. 138</figureCitation>
); 3) penes base large (bp in 
<figureCitation box="[938,1035,1940,1965]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Fig. 138</figureCitation>
), main lobe of penes thin, long and cylindrical, curved ventromedially (ml in 
<figureCitation box="[633,800,1976,2001]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Figs. 138–139</figureCitation>
), secondary lobe of penes long and slender (sl in 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="338">Figs. 138–139</figureCitation>
) but shorter than main lobe; 4) small size (length of male fore wings 
<quantity box="[1033,1131,2012,2036]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="37" pageNumber="338" unit="mm" value="7.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="7.0">7–8 mm</quantity>
); 5) female sockets formed by a long, thin furrow ending in two separated but contiguous sockets (
<figureCitation box="[955,1121,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 146 – 150" captionStartId="40.[151,264,1639,1662]" captionTargetBox="[226,1361,195,1618]" captionTargetId="figure@40.[226,1361,195,1618]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURES 146 – 150. C. segnis (specimens from Venezuela): 146, male imago, abdomen, laterodorsal view; 147, female imago, abdomen, d. v.; 148, female head and thorax, v. v. (fs = mesofurcasternum, im = inner margin, p = mesofurcasternal plates, L = middle legs); 149, abdominal sterna (g = gonopore and eggs, sk = sockets, roman numbers = segment number); 150, detail of sockets (arrows indicate socket´s openings)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838474/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="339">Figs. 149–150</figureCitation>
); 6) eggs without polar cap, with amorphous structure on convex side.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
