<subSubSection pageId="39" pageNumber="340" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1436,151,248]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,151,176]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Needham &amp; Murphy ." authorityYear="1924" box="[340,547,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="segnis">
<emphasis box="[340,547,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Campsurus segnis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Traver (1947)" authorityName="Traver" authorityYear="1947" box="[700,973,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ulmeri">
<emphasis box="[700,808,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">C. ulmeri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Traver" box="[817,973,152,176]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" refString="Traver, J. R. (1947) Notes on Neotropical mayflies. Part III. Family Ephemeridae. Revista de Entomologia, 18, 370 - 395." type="journal article" year="1947">Traver (1947)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and to 
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[1062,1170,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cotaxe" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1062,1170,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">C. cotaxe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1178,1270,151,176]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1178,1270,151,176]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
because all of them have pedestals that are distinctly separated in the middle, a relatively long parastylus and thin, long and cylindrical penes lobes. Details that separate these species are discused below.
</paragraph>
